{"id":"1206.5522","submitter":"John Francis","authors":"David Ayala, John Francis","title":"Factorization homology of topological manifolds","comments":"37 pages. Accepted for publication by Journal of Topology","journal-ref":"J. Topol. 8 (2015), no. 4, 1045-1084","doi":"10.1112/jtopol/jtv028","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AT math.GT math.QA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Factorization homology theories of topological manifolds, after Beilinson,\nDrinfeld and Lurie, are homology-type theories for topological $n$-manifolds\nwhose coefficient systems are $n$-disk algebras or $n$-disk stacks. In this\nwork we prove a precise formulation of this idea, giving an axiomatic\ncharacterization of factorization homology with coefficients in $n$-disk\nalgebras in terms of a generalization of the Eilenberg--Steenrod axioms for\nsingular homology. Each such theory gives rise to a kind of topological quantum\nfield theory, for which observables can be defined on general $n$-manifolds and\nnot only closed $n$-manifolds. For $n$-disk algebra coefficients, these field\ntheories are characterized by the condition that global observables are\ndetermined by local observables in a strong sense. Our axiomatic point of view\nhas a number of applications. In particular, we give a concise proof of the\nnonabelian Poincar\\'e duality of Salvatore, Segal, and Lurie. We present some\nessential classes of calculations of factorization homology, such as for free\n$n$-disk algebras and enveloping algebras of Lie algebras, several of which\nhave a conceptual meaning in terms of Koszul duality.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 24 Jun 2012 17:05:33 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 29 Aug 2013 16:00:58 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 22 Apr 2014 01:47:46 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 13 May 2015 22:13:52 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Tue, 18 Aug 2015 21:29:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-05-17"}
