{"id":"1206.5556","submitter":"Jos\\'e Simental-Rodr\\'iguez","authors":"Chris Holston, Sergio R. L\\'opez-Permouth, Joe Mastromatteo, Jos\\'e E.\n  Simental-Rodr\\'iguez","title":"An alternative perspective on projectivity of modules","comments":"Dedicated to the memory of Francisco Raggi; v2 some editorial\n  changes. 'Right hereditary right perfect' replaced by the (equivalent)\n  condition 'right hereditary semiprimary'; v3 a mistake corrected in the\n  statements of Propositions 3.8 and 3.9","journal-ref":"Glasgow Math. J. 57 (1), 2015, 83-99","doi":"10.1017/S0017089514000135","report-no":null,"categories":"math.RA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Similar to the idea of relative projectivity, we introduce the notion of\nrelative subprojectivity, which is an alternative way to measure the\nprojectivity of a module. Given modules $M$ and $N$, $M$ is said to be {\\em\n$N$-subprojective} if for every epimorphism $g:B \\rightarrow N$ and\nhomomorphism $f:M \\rightarrow N$, then there exists a homomorphism $h:M\n\\rightarrow B$ such that $gh=f$. For a module $M$, the {\\em subprojectivity\ndomain of $M$} is defined to be the collection of all modules $N$ such that $M$\nis $N$-subprojective. A module is projective if and only if its subprojectivity\ndomain consists of all modules. Opposite to this idea, a module $M$ is said to\nbe {\\em subprojectively poor}, or {\\em $sp$-poor} if its subprojectivity domain\nis as small as conceivably possible, that is, consisting of exactly the\nprojective modules. Properties of subprojectivity domains and $sp$-poor modules\nare studied. In particular, the existence of an $sp$-poor module is attained\nfor artinian serial rings.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 25 Jun 2012 01:32:38 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 2 Aug 2013 18:21:19 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 16 Aug 2013 21:42:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-20"}
